correlation = abs(data.corr())
lower_triangle = np.tril(correlation, k=-1)
mask = lower_triangle == 0

plt.figure(figsize=(15,10))
sns.set_style(style='white')
sns.heatmap(lower_triangle, center=.5, cmap='Blues', annot=True, 
            xticklabels=correlation.index, yticklabels=correlation.columns,
            cbar=False, linewidths=1, mask=mask)
plt.show();

Insights¶

There is very little linear correlation between individual properties. The biggest correlations are between Balance and NumOfProducts, and between Age and Exited, but even these correlations are low. This doesn't mean there is no correlation, only that it is not linear. Good dataset for a neural network.

Modelling¶

Initialize and build the model; identify points of improvement and implement, 20pts

In [16]:
from tensorflow import keras
from tensorflow.keras import Sequential
from tensorflow.keras.layers import Dense
from tensorflow.keras.optimizers import SGD
In [17]:
keras.backend.set_floatx('float64')

model = Sequential()

opt = SGD(lr=.005, momentum=.9)

# 11-node input layer and 9-node hidden layer
model.add(Dense(9, input_shape=(11,), activation='elu'))

# Single output neuron
model.add(Dense(1, activation='sigmoid'))

model.compile(loss='binary_crossentropy', optimizer=opt, metrics=['accuracy'])

history = model.fit(x_train, y_train, epochs=2500, batch_size=4096, verbose=0, validation_data=(x_test, y_test))
In [18]:
train_loss, train_acc = model.evaluate(x_train, y_train, verbose=0)
test_loss, test_acc = model.evaluate(x_test, y_test, verbose=0)

print('Training Accuracy: %.3f' % train_acc)
print('Testing Accuracy: %.3f' % test_acc)
print('')
print('Training Loss: %.3f' % train_loss)
print('Testing Loss: %.3f' % test_loss)

plt.title('Loss')
plt.plot(history.history['loss'], label='train')
plt.plot(history.history['val_loss'], label='test')
plt.legend()
plt.show()

plt.title('Accuracy')
plt.plot(history.history['accuracy'], label='train')
plt.plot(history.history['val_accuracy'], label='test')
plt.legend()
plt.show()

Model Performance Evaluation¶

Print accuracy score and confusion matrix, 5pts

In [22]:
from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score, confusion_matrix, precision_score, recall_score, f1_score

y_pred_cls = model.predict_classes(x_test, batch_size=200, verbose=0)

print('Accuracy: ' + str(model.evaluate(x_test, y_test.values)[1]))
print('Recall: ' + str(recall_score(y_test.values, y_pred_cls)))
print('Precision score: ' + str(precision_score(y_test.values, y_pred_cls)))
print('F-score: ' + str(f1_score(y_test.values, y_pred_cls)))

cm = confusion_matrix(y_test.values, y_pred_cls)

group_names = ['True Negative',
               'False Positive',
               'False Negative',
               'True Positive']

group_counts = ["{0:0.0f}".format(value) for value in cm.flatten()]
group_percs = ["{0:.2%}".format(value) for value in cm.flatten()/np.sum(cm)]

labels = [f"{v1}\n{v2}\n{v3}" for v1, v2, v3 in zip(group_names, group_counts, group_percs)]
labels = np.asarray(labels).reshape(2,2)

sns.heatmap(cm, annot=labels, fmt='', cmap='Blues');
